[
    {
        "content": "<p>Have there been any talks about implementing field selection like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>selection = record.{ fields1, field2, fields3.{ subfield1, subfield2 } }\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Basically the in the same way that it is used for imports.</p>\n<p>This could be useful in reducing the noise in field selection, for example in GraphQL clients.</p>\n<p>Another option would be with expressions. Something like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>with = \\target, fields -&gt; List.map fields \\f -&gt; f target\n\nwith record [.field1, .field2]\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>But that outputs a list instead of a record, and therefore requires encapsulating data in tags.</p>",
        "id": 434493205,
        "sender_full_name": "Niclas Overby",
        "timestamp": 1713612549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The current syntax for accessing records fields is <code>.field1</code> which is the same as a function <code>{ field1 }_ -&gt; field1</code> I think. Is that similar?</p>",
        "id": 434496046,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1713615059
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually that is in the tutorial <a href=\"https://www.roc-lang.org/tutorial#record-shorthands\">https://www.roc-lang.org/tutorial#record-shorthands</a></p>",
        "id": 434496162,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1713615146
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nvm me, I misread your idea.</p>",
        "id": 434496208,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1713615200
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like the syntax of the first one similar to imports.</p>",
        "id": 434496344,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1713615339
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So that is creating a selection record that just copies a bunch of fields from the result record?</p>\n<p>The output record is this?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elixir\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">selection</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">fields1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">field2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"ss\">fields3</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"ss\">subfield1</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"ss\">subfield2</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"c1\"># dropped any other sub fields</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">},</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\"># dropped any other fields</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 434506788,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1713624352
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or does it flatten the selected fields?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elixir\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">selection</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"ss\">fields1</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"ss\">field2</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"ss\">subfields1</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"ss\">subfields2</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">...</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 434507133,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1713624544
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Either way, I don't quite understand the goal. You can always pass the original record to a function that takes an open record and uses a subset of the fields.</p>\n<p>Ex:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elixir\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">record</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\"># my original gigantic record</span>\n\n<span class=\"n\">subFieldFunc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"err\">\\</span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"n\">fields1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">field2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ss\">fields3</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">subfield1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">subfield2</span><span class=\"p\">}}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\"># use all the fields</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\"># could even directly return</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"n\">fields1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">field2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">subfield1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">subfield2</span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"n\">subFieldFunc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">record</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 434507486,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1713624818
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"343810\">@Brendan Hansknecht</span>  <code>record.{ fields1, field2, fields3.{ subfield1, subfield2 } }</code> is briefer than using a function and opening the record with that.</p>",
        "id": 434563191,
        "sender_full_name": "Niclas Overby",
        "timestamp": 1713679743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You don't even need to define a function. You can use pattern-matching locally like so:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>selection =\n    { fields1, fields2, fields3: { subfield1, subfield2 } } = record\n    { fields1, fields2, fields3: { subfield1, subfield2 } }\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 434564300,
        "sender_full_name": "timotree",
        "timestamp": 1713681021
    }
]